## Migration Analysis

**APIs found that won't work on .NET 8:**

| API | Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` via `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop fallback | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call that needs waking | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token |

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+. `Thread.Interrupt()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9+).

---

## Bug in the original code

The original has a **lost-signal race**: if `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, `ManualResetEvent` is `Set` twice (no-op the second time), then `Reset` once — but only **one** item is dequeued. The second item stays in the queue until the next enqueue.

---

## Migrated Code (direct translation with CancellationToken)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either a new event arrives OR cancellation is requested
            WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle]);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain ALL queued items — fixes the lost-signal race in the original
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // signals token.WaitHandle, waking the thread
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // still gives 5s for graceful shutdown
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `while(true)` → `while(!token.IsCancellationRequested)`
- `_newEvent.WaitOne()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle])`
- `Thread.Interrupt()` + `Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()` (one call replaces both)
- `ManualResetEvent` → `ManualResetEventSlim` (lighter weight)
- Implements `IDisposable` (CTS and event are disposable)
- Drain loop fixes the lost-signal bug

---

## Modern Alternative: `Channel<T>` (recommended)

For .NET 8, `Channel<T>` replaces the manual queue + event + lock entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }  // expected on shutdown
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();       // signals no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));  // timeout fallback
        if (_task is not null)
            await _task;
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

This eliminates the `Thread`, `ManualResetEvent`, and explicit `lock` entirely.

---

## Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | If `Handle(item)` takes 30s, `Stop()` blocks until it finishes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `Handle` if it does lengthy work. |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | CTS is `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. |
| **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (the loop runner), not inside `Handle`. |
| **`Thread.Abort` had no graceful guarantee** | The old code could corrupt state mid-operation. The new cooperative model is *safer* — but you must actually check the token. |
| **`Thread.Interrupt` only worked in `WaitSleepJoin` state** | The original `Stop()` was already fragile — if the thread was in `Handle()`, `Interrupt` did nothing until the next `WaitOne`. The new approach has the same timing, but is explicit about it. |
